---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const title = 'Product Liability Guides | productliabilitycalc.com';
const description = 'In-depth guides on product liability: settlement calculation methodology, defect theories, what to do after an injury, and the most common misconceptions.';
---
<BaseLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <h1>Product Liability Guides</h1>
  <p><em>Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>Long-form references on the topics that come up most often for readers of this site. Each guide is written for a non-lawyer and is sourced to the controlling statutes, regulations, and case law. Use them alongside the <a href="/">home-page calculator</a> and the <a href="/methodology">methodology</a> page.</p>

  <h2>The guides</h2>

  <h3><a href="/guides/how-product-liability-settlements-are-calculated">How product liability settlements are calculated</a></h3>
  <p>A full walkthrough of how a product liability settlement is built: economic damages, non-economic damages, multipliers, punitive exposure, defendant insurance, and the jurisdictional adjustments that move recovery up or down. The companion piece to the calculator's methodology page, written for a reader who wants the underlying math explained.</p>

  <h3><a href="/guides/types-of-product-defects-and-claim-theories">Types of product defects and claim theories</a></h3>
  <p>Design defect, manufacturing defect, and failure-to-warn explained end-to-end, with classic examples from auto, pharma, and consumer-product litigation. Covers the consumer-expectation and risk-utility tests, the learned-intermediary doctrine, breach of warranty, and consumer-fraud claims that typically run alongside the strict-liability count.</p>

  <h3><a href="/guides/what-to-do-after-a-defective-product-injury">What to do after a defective product injury</a></h3>
  <p>A practical, step-by-step guide to the first 30 days after an injury caused by a defective product. Covers product preservation (the single most important step), medical documentation, scene photography, witness statements, recall research, statute-of-limitations alerts, and how to evaluate a plaintiff-side product liability lawyer.</p>

  <h3><a href="/guides/common-product-liability-claim-misconceptions">Common product liability claim misconceptions</a></h3>
  <p>Fifteen myths about product liability cases, debunked. Covers the McDonald's coffee case, the "frivolous lawsuit" framing, federal preemption, statute of repose, used-product claims, comparative-fault rules, contingency fees, and the difference between recall and personal injury claims.</p>

  <h2>How to use the guides</h2>

  <p>Read in any order. If you have just been injured, start with the practical guide on what to do after a defective-product injury. If you want to understand why your case is worth what it might be worth, start with the calculation methodology. If you are unsure which defect theory applies, start with the defect-theory guide. If you are trying to evaluate something a lawyer told you (or something you read on a law-firm marketing page), start with the misconceptions guide.</p>

  <p>For additional context, the <a href="/case-types">case types</a> page walks through the major product categories, the <a href="/faq">FAQ</a> answers the most common quick questions, and the <a href="/editorial">editorial</a> page identifies the contributors and our editorial standards.</p>
</BaseLayout>
